TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Elimination form of the Inverse and its Application to Linear Programming
AU  - Markowitz, Harry M.
Y1  - 1957/04/01
PY  - 1957
DA  - 1957/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.3.3.255
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.3.3.255
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 255
EP  - 269
VL  - 3
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - It is common for matrices in industrial applications of linear programming to have a large proportion of zero coefficients. While every item (raw material, intermediate material, end item, equipment item) in, say, a petroleum refinery may be indirectly related to every other, any particular process uses few of these. Thus the matrix describing petroleum technology has a small percentage of non-zeros. If spacial or temporal distinctions are introduced into the model the percentage of non-zeros generally falls further. The present paper discusses a form of inverse which is especially convenient to obtain and use for matrices with a high percentage of zeros. The application of this form of inverse in linear programming is also discussed.
AB  - It is common for matrices in industrial applications of linear programming to have a large proportion of zero coefficients. While every item (raw material, intermediate material, end item, equipment item) in, say, a petroleum refinery may be indirectly related to every other, any particular process uses few of these. Thus the matrix describing petroleum technology has a small percentage of non-zeros. If spacial or temporal distinctions are introduced into the model the percentage of non-zeros generally falls further. The present paper discusses a form of inverse which is especially convenient to obtain and use for matrices with a high percentage of zeros. The application of this form of inverse in linear programming is also discussed.
